Related Material at the New York University Archives
There are two interviews regarding the history department with professors Carl Prince and David Hicks in the Records of the NYU Public History Program Box 15, folders 6 and 7.
Scope and Content Note
This collection contains administrative records of the History Department. Materials include staff files, budget information, and correspondence.
Historical Note
The Department of History is located within the Faculty of Arts and Science at NYU. History has been taught at NYU since the University's founding in 1831, but it was not until 1893 that NYU formed academic departments, including one in history. Courses are offered to undergraduates and graduates.
Preferred Citation
Published citations should take the following form:
Identification of item, date (if known); The Records of the History Department of the Faculty of Arts and Science; RG 21.3; box number; folder number;

Use Restrictions
Any rights (including copyright and related rights to publicity and privacy) held by the creator are maintained by New York University. Permission to publish or reproduce materials in this collection must be secured from New York University Archives, (212) 998-2646, university-archives@nyu.edu.
Access Restrictions
Administrative records and unpublished reports of New York University are closed for a period of 20 years from the date of their creation. Access to files spanning multiple years will be opened to researchers based on the date of the most recent materials. Board of Trustees records are closed for 35 years from the date of creation. Materials related to personnel, grievances, job and fellowship searches and applications, and all files that fall under the federal Family Educational Rights and Privacy Act (FERPA) are permanently restricted. Additional restrictions may apply to other materials in this collection. For questions regarding specific restrictions, please contact the University Archives.
Provenance
This collection was transferred to the University Archives from the History Department.
